  </oversight_info>
  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      The antioxidant system of very low birth weight infants is immature. This immaturity is
      implicated in the pathogenesis of diseases such as bronchopulmonary dysplasia or retinopathy.
      The main source of oxidant is oxygen, and parenteral nutrition is contaminated with oxidant.
      Photoprotection decreases the oxidant load infused with parenteral nutrition. In a
      preliminary study, photoprotection reduced the frequency of pulmonary bronchodysplasia,
      increased the quantity of enteral nutrition tolerated, and decreased the arterial blood
      pressure among very low birth weight infants. The aim of this study is to evaluate the impact
      of photoprotection on oxidant related diseases among very low birth weight infants. This
      study is a randomized multicenter trial. In the intervention group, photoprotection is
      applied until the infusion of parenteral nutrition with amber bags, tubing, and syringes. The
      quality of photoprotection is controlled by measuring malondialdehyde and cysteine after 24
      hours of infusion. The control group will receive parenteral nutrition with transparent bags
      and tubing. The outcomes are evaluated at 36 weeks, and 680 infants will be enrolled, with
      stratification among centers and gestational age.
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
